.537 in the\nsame period last year.\nNovember foreclosure* de- 1\ncllned to 850 from 993 In the\nprevious month and were well\nbelow 963 In November last\nyear. Foreclosures totaled 703\nIn 11 months, compared with\n823 a year earlier. I\nID. C. Agency Writes Folicv\nFar Brussels Exhibits\nSeveral million dollars worth\nof American exhibits for the\n1958 World's Fair in Brussels, i\nBelgium, will be protected un-j\nder an unusual inland-ocean\nmarine Insurance policy writ\nten by a Hartford insurance\ncompany through a Washing\nton agency.\nThe coverage drafted by the\nmarine department of Aetna\nInsurance Co. in co-operation\nwith the McLaughlin Co. of\nWashington became effective\nNovember 1 although the ex\nhibit will not open its doors\nuntil next April. The policy\nexpires March 1. 1959.\nThe covered property is\nbeing borrowed by the United\nStates Government from pri\nvate individuals and organisa\ntions\nTotal value of the exhibits is\nestimated at more than $6 mil\nlion. but liability of the parti\ncipating companies is limited\nto about half of the total.\nOther participating companies\nare Home Insurance Co.. Queen\nInsurance Co.. Great American\nInsurance. Maryland Casualty.\nInsurance Co. of North Amer\nica and Firemen's Fund Insur\nance.\nWarid Bank te Market\nIssue es 21-Tear Bends\nThe International Bank for\nReconstruction and Develop\nment announced a new 9150\nmillion offering in mid-Jahuary\nwill consist of 21-year bonds\nthat will be noncallable prior\nto January 15. 1965.\nBeginning in 1965 a sinking\nfund will be in effect calculated\nto retire 50 per cent of the\nissue by maturity.\nOffering will be made\nthrough a Nation-wide syndi\ncate of Investment bankers,\nsecurities dealers and commer\ncial banks headed Jointly by;\nFirst Boston Corp. and Morgan\nStanley St Co.\nThe bank again will extend\nto certain institutional pur\nchasers the privilege of making\ndelayed payments, giving them\na selection of specified de\nlivery dates between April IS,\n1955. and January 15, 1961.\nWashington Gas Votes\nQuarterly Dividends\nDirectors of Washington Oas\nLight Co. have declared quar-\u2018\n.terly dividends of Sl.lS's\nshare on the cumulative con\nvertible preferred stock and\n91.06 Vo a share on $4.25 cumu\nlative preferred, both payable\nFebruary 10 to stockholders of\nrecord January 24.\nThey also declared a quar\nterly dividend of 50 cents a\nshare on common stock, pay\nable February 1 to holders of\nrecord January 15.\nCUfton Corp. Moros\nTo New Quarter*\nClifton Corp.. management\nand personnel consultants, has\nmoved to new quarters In the\nMarsh Building. 1832 M street.\nN W\nThe firm has been located at\n1621 Connecticut avenue N.W..\nfor more than 10 years.\nHigh Officials Appointed\nFor Greensboro FHLB\nChairmen and vice chairmen\nhave been appointed for the\nFederal Home Loan Bank of\nGreensboro, N. C.. of which\nsavings and loan associations\nof the Washington area are\nmembers.\nHorace 8. Haworth, attorney\nof High Point. N. C., will serve;\nas chairman of the institution\nfor the coming year. It was an\nnounced by Chairman Albert J.\nRobertson of the Federal Home\nLoan Bank Board.\nClarendon Trust Co.\nOpens Motor Bank\nThe Clarendon Trust Co.\nopened Its new Motor Bsnk in\nnearby Virginia this morning.\nLocated on Washington\nboulevard at Kann's Virginia\nsquare shopping center, the\nnew facility has three teller\nwindows and will cater to mo\ntorists. It is three blocks sway\nfrom the bank\u2019s main office.\nIt will be open from 8 am\nto 8 p.m. on weekdays. Satur\nday hours will be 8 a m. to noon.\nMr. a*b\u00bbr Mr. Lswm\u00ab4\nS\nDresser Elects\n2 New Executive\nVice Presidents\nDALLAS. Tex.. Dec 26 (Spe\ncial).\u2014Directors of Dresser In\ndustries. Inc., today elected two\nnew executive vice presidents.\nI They are R. E. Relmer and\nJohn Lawrence.\nThe former also will con\ntinue as treasurer. The latter\nrecently resigned as president\nof Joy Manufacturing Co. to\njoin Dresser as a vice president.\nThomas L. Moody. Dresser's\nindustrial relatioris director for\n15 years, was promoted to vice\npresident and J. Douglas May\nson was promoted from assist\nant secretary to secretary.\nCecil C. Hill and Paul E. Brod\nrick were named asslstam\ntreasurers.\nSHOP TONIGHT TO 9 Mondays, Thursdays and Fridays\nSTORE HOURS: Mondays, 12:30 to 9; Tuesdays, Wednesdays and\nSaturdays, 10 to 6; Thursdays and Fridays, 10 to 9. Free Parking!\njtfc SB A sp wF M H\nSniOV/0 TRADE-IN\nON SECOND TIRE\nv\nr ALLSTATE\nr# COMPANIONS\nBVfrn Full 15-Month Guarantee\nB tllll BUY FIRST TIRE AT\nWSUttJ- REGULAR NO TRADE-IN\nPRICE PLUS TAX\n(COMPANION TUBE-TYPE BLACKWALLS AND TWO OLD TIRES\n\u25a0SwVJII Buy Flew _ ff REGARDLESS OF CONDITION\nmfliUettW Tire At W\nReguler Ne p,,t w jQM\n*Ti\u00bb 4 u T Frin r Here's rugged dependability priced to suit every budget\nCharge I* \u2019\u00ab7O- ic 17\u20197V p, T **_' _ Free Wheel Tough X-41\u2019 Cold Rubber fights punctures ond tire fatigue\nat Sears! 7 in!!ic IQ qc 0 Q7 a no\u2019 Rototion Every Tread design for more rood-bite traction in all weather\nI\u2122,!! 11S-I 5000 MiU\nr ONLY 10% DOWN ON SEARS EASY PAYMENT PLAN\nTh\u00ab Premium Tiro of the Century! Full 20-Month Guarantor!\nALLSTATE. ALLSTATE\nGUARDSMAN CUSHIONS\n24\u201d m\nAND YOUR OLD TIRE W AND YOUR OLD TIRt\nREGARDLESS OF CONDITION Ml 1 REGARDLESS OF CONDITION\no Full 30-Month Mali an wide Guarantee Rubber Safety Button* between\n\u2022gainst hazards wherever you drive ffOf\u00df tr s reduce dengereuo skid*\n30% Deepet, durable tread gives ti\u00ab\u00abtax 1 tiuin 1 i\u00abV>- piu,*to\u00ab pi*i\u00ab P \u00b0V> tough X-41 Cold Rubber fights\nyou up to 30% more snileage e.TOeis i0.\u00ab5 less 5.00 6.7osis 21.4 s ia.se t 4.00 common tire stress end strain\n7.loefS 12.9 S I 27.0$ S.SO fm 7.10x15 25.7 S 20.69 4.00\n0 Rugged Nylon Cord resists damage 7.6oeis i\u00ab.ss I 30.2$ e.oo W 7.6o*is 25.2 S 1 22.6$ 1 4.50 O Bonded Rayon Cord Body cushMOna\nRem moisture and heat fenetratio* i.oopis D 0.90 3Q.ss 1 7.00 i.ooiis 1 11.90 27.5$ s.so eheeb esNisad by tocke end bumps\n*\u00ab\u00abri t Stortt H ri I 3tortt\nV* S 0 4V _ Ale. Avt. at Neyta* HE. s.l. (20) LUfflew I-1100\nC>a^Z)4adiiM'pMVUZrt&taot VOM/n&tey fact XIADC xrraftSi'VMi-.v.SS: ES\n_ 0 1 JLHIXJ 00 DWL Arlingtsn -49\u00ab\u00bb\n1 I4SS CriMvills R 4\u201e Silvat Spring ....JUnipar 9-9010\n1 f\nyoua\nMONEY S WORTH W\nr SYLViA FOETEE\nW/iot You Said at Christmas\nNow begins the season for\nsecond-guessing the Christmas\nisles pattern\u2014and from coast\nto coast tn the next several\ndays, businessmen, bankers,\neconomists will be toting up the\nfigures, trying to decide what\nthey foretell for 1958.\nWell, even before the final\nstatistics are in and before\nthe authorities come out with\ntheir carefully phrased ex\nplanations and forece-sta. I can\nreport some deeply significant\npoints about 1957's Christmas\nbuying period. During the past\n30 days, you have made it un\nmistakably clear that:\nYou have become more cagey\nabout buying than in many a\nyear.\nYou have become perceptibly\nmore price-conscious.\nYou have returned to your\nprewar habit of buying late In\nthe season because you are\nfully aware that the era of\nshortages Is over.\nYou are responding to sales,\nbargain promotions.\nYou know that you're king\nand queen of the marketplace\nand you are insisting on being\n\"sold\u201d a product or service be\nlore you buy.\nYou are still willing to buy\nmassive totals of goods and\nservices.\nHow do all these points\nemerge about you? Through\ndevelopments that don't al\nways show up in the dollar\ntotals. For instance:\ni U) For the first time since\nWorld War 11. there was a\ndefinite shift in many areas\nto goods and gifts in the lower\nprice ranges* s tendency to\n\"trade down\" on buying\nFrom merchant after mer\nchant. I heard such comments\nas these: \"We're selling more\nof our lower-priced lines than\nat any time in the past 10\nyears. We're getting the\nbest play in the cheaper blends\n(apparel. Our bargain\nbasement got the* big crowds!\nthis year.\n(3> TTUs Christmas, you by\npassed the mink-decorated pot\nholder and went in for prod\nucts that are functional and\nutilitarian.\nI Typical quotes: \"People came\nIn. looked at our exquisite\nglass decorations, then bought\nan ash tray or a set of break\nfast dishes Apparel was\na big seller and people were\nconcentrating on the sort of\nkids can Wear every day.\nThe trend was even apparent\nin our toy department; best\nsellers were functional toys and\nscience stuff went over big..\n(3 1 You patronized most\nheavily the lower-medium price\ndepartments of big stores, the\ncut-rate shops, supermarkets,\nsuper drugstores.\nMore typical quotes: \"We\npulled in our customers by\nshouting about our bargains\nand did fine. We realized\nthe public was getting price\nconscious months ago and em\nphasized our best buys. That\u2019s\nwhy we made out so well and\nthat's going to be our theme\nfor 1958\nEach of these points under\nlines your new attitudes\u2014your\ncaution .your price conscious\nness. your \"sell me first\" ap\nproach.\nYet. despite these attitudes\nof yours and despite the fact\nthat you have been struggling\naaa'nst the sobering influences\nof flu. Sputnik, a declining\nstock market, rising Joblessness,\nworld tensipns, etc., etc., you\nstill bought fabulous amounts\nof good* as the season came\nto an end.\nSo what does It foretell for\n1958?\nThe merchants will have to\nsell and sell, promote and\npromote, advertise and adver\ntise to move the goods. You've\ngiven them the signal: You\u2019ll\nbuy but they'll have to sell you\nfirst.\nAnd you 11 get plenty of good\nbuys in 1958\n(Dlxtrr.uWd I\u00bb*7 kr Th\u00bb H\u00abl)\nSyndic it*. Inr All RlgtoU Rutrted)\n'SB Downturn Unlikely,\nNew York Group Says\nNEW YORK.. Dec. 26 UP).\u2014\nA business downturn is not in\ni the cards next year, at least not\nfor New York, the Commerce\nand Industry Association of\nNew York says.\n\"Currently publicized talk of\na business downturn ahead evi\ndently is not backed by the\nfacts.\u201d said Gliomas J. Miley,\nthe association's executive vice\npresident yesterday.\nOs 418 firms participating in\na survey, 30.2 per cent expect\ntheir business in 1958 to aver\nage 15 per cent better than in\n1957 and another 47.4 per cent\nthink it will be at least as good\nas It was this year, he said.\nCommerce Department\nPoints to Leveling Off\nOeneral business activity has\nshown some easing from peak\n.rates of last summer, the De\npartment of Commerce reported\nin its Burvey of Current Busi\nness.\nA leveling of prices and a\nlessening in the intensity of\ndemands in the money and\ncapital markets also were noted.\nMonthly Indicators of the\nNation's business edged down\nward in November, extending\ndeclines which were first evi\ndenced on a general scale In\nOctober, the report said. Size\nof these declines has been quite\nmodest, with the economy as a\nwhole currently functioning at\nhigh, near-record rates.\nPersonal income in Novem-\nber was at an annual rate of\n1 8345.5 billion, compared with\nf the August'Beptember peak of\naround $347 billion.\nAn exception to the pattern\nia afforded by construction ac\ntivity. which in the past few\nmonths has made a somewhat\nimproved showing and has been\na strengthening influence in\n1 the economy, the report added.\nCompared with a year ago.\nconstruction volume was up 4\nper cent in November and 2\nper cent higher in 11 months.\nCHI\u2019GQ UVISTOCK\nCHICAGO. Dec 26 on <U\u00bbDAi.\u2014\nSalable hogs active; butcher* 2A\nto mostlr 50 higher, bat closing trade\ni only 25 higher, sows strong to fully 25\nhigher. 2-3 IDO-230 lb butehers\n20 00-20.50; more uniform 1-3 190-\n220 lb* *0 50-20 75. 100 head more\nI uniform mostly 1-2 s around 215 lbs\n20 85; 2-3 230-250 lha J 9 50-20.25;\n,250-270 lb* mostly 2-3 trades 19 25-\n20.00; tome 270-300 lbs mostly 3*\n19.50-19 50; larger lot* mixed trade\nL 375-550 lb sow* 15 25-10 50; a few\n;too-3f\u00bbo lb* 15 50-17.00 fair clear\nance fair shipping demand\nSalable cattle 4.000; calves 100;\nchoice and prime steers active, steady\nto ft<\u00bb higher, good and below slow.\nsteady to 50 lower, heifers mostly\nsteady; rows steady to 25 higher;\nother classes strong mixed choice and\nprime steer* 2* 00-30.00; balk choice\nsteers 25.00-27.75; mixed good ana\nchoice 25 25-25 75. good 23 00-26 0<\u00bb;\nseveral load* standard 21 .#9l-22.00;\ni half a load prime 9*2 lb heifers 2* 00;\na few loads choice and prime 26.50-\n27.50: standard and good i9.00-24.R0;\nutility and commercial cows 15.00-\n17.60; canners and cutters 12.00\u2019\n16.60. utility and commercial bulls\n1 50-21.00; good and choice vealers\n25.00-30.00 a few culls as low as\n15 00. a load of low good 51 o lb stock\nsteers 26 25; choice 1.055 lbs feeding\nsteers 23 *5","height":"28475","width":"18244"}}
